South African Stocks Climb For a Fourth Day; AngloGold BHP Billiton Rally

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-05-27T15:45:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-27/south-africa-stocks-rise-for-4th-day-anglogold-ashanti-impala-are-active.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rallied for a fourth day, adding 404.30, or 1.3 percent, to
32,384.41 at the 5 p.m. close of trade in Johannesburg,
extending its increase this week to 1.9 percent, the biggest
since the five days through April 1.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of  South Africa ’s benchmark stock
index, increased for a fourth day, adding 4.93 rand, or 1.5
percent, to 341.10 rand. Copper rose to a three-week high as
increased premiums signaled stronger demand in China and
Standard Chartered Plc predicted price gains, joining banks
including Goldman Sachs Group Inc.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, rose for a fourth day, adding 2.18 rand, or 0.8
percent, to 271.88 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s biggest gold
producer, gained 4.30 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 313.40 rand,
paring yesterday’s 1.8 percent loss. Gold advanced as sovereign-
debt concerns in  Europe  boosted demand for an investment haven.
Harmony Gold Mining Co. Ltd. (HAR SJ), the third-largest
supplier, jumped the most since April 6, climbing 2.49 rand, or
2.7 percent, to 93.50 rand.  Bidvest Group Ltd. (BVT)  , a diversified investment
group, had the highest close in a month, gaining 3.24 rand, or
2.2 percent, to 151.99 rand. The company held a presentation to
explain its divisions’ operations to analysts and investors
today. The event was closed to the media.  Brikor Ltd. (BIK)  , a South African paving and brick
manufacturer, advanced the most since Jan. 10, rising 2 cents,
or 25 percent, to 10 cents. The company said in a statement it
expects to report a loss per share after one-time items of as
much as 7 cents a share in the year ended February, compared
with a loss of 5.5 cents a year earlier.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the world’s second-
largest platinum producer, rallied 3.29 rand, or 1.8 percent, to
186.50 rand, the highest close since May 16. Platinum rose as
much as 1.3 percent. Separately, Impala is undertaking a full
strategic review of its Marula operation, which has continued to
underperform, Impala said in a statement.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, increased for the fourth day, jumping 6.95 rand,
or 1.9 percent, to 364.95 rand. Oil climbed as much as 1 percent
to $101.24 a barrel.  Universal Industries Corp. (UNI SJ), the South African
supplier of fridges to supermarkets, jumped to a record,
rallying 23 cents, or 13 percent, to 2.05 rand. The company said
it received a non-binding expression of interest that may result
in an offer being made for its shares, Universal said in a
regulatory statement today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
